<li id="cite_note-O&#39;Reilly2010-71"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-O&#39;Reilly2010_71-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFO&#39;Reilly2010" class="citation book cs1">O'Reilly, Andrea (6 April 2010). <i>Encyclopedia of Motherhood</i>. SAGE Publications. p.&#160;1056. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781452266299" title="Special:BookSources/9781452266299"><bdi>9781452266299</bdi></a>. <q>The Roman Catholic church and some Protestant denominations have approved only "natural family planning" methods--including the rhythm method and periodic abstinence.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopedia+of+Motherhood&amp;rft.pages=1056&amp;rft.pub=SAGE+Publications&amp;rft.date=2010-04-06&amp;rft.isbn=9781452266299&amp;rft.aulast=O%27Reilly&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrea&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AChristian+views+on+marriage" class="Z3988"></span></span>
